Let $p,$ $q,$ $r,$ $s,$ and $t$ be the distinct roots of the equation $x^5 - 3x^3 + 1 = 0.$ Find the value of
\begin{align*}
&\frac{p^4}{(p - q)(p - r)(p - s)(p - t)} + \frac{q^4}{(q - p)(q - r)(q - s)(q - t)} \\
&\quad + \frac{r^4}{(r - p)(r - q)(r - s)(r - t)} + \frac{s^4}{(s - p)(s - q)(s - r)(s - t)} \\
&\quad + \frac{t^4}{(t - p)(t - q)(t - r)(t - s)}.
\end{align*}

variant_solution:
Consider the polynomial $f(x) = x^5 - 3x^3 + 1$ with distinct roots $p, q, r, s, t.$ We want to evaluate the sum
\begin{align*}
S = \sum_{k \in \{p, q, r, s, t\}} \frac{k^4}{\prod_{\substack{j \in \{p, q, r, s, t\} \\ j \neq k}} (k - j)}.
\end{align*}
This sum is known to be equal to the coefficient of $x^4$ in the polynomial $f(x),$ which is $0$ for $f(x) = x^5 - 3x^3 + 1.$ Therefore, the value of $S$ is $0.$

